Anonymous Fri 20 Mar 2020 01:42:18 No.29068847 Report

>>29068631
Inspiration is an important, if not *the* most important part of writing. You can be a terrible writer, but if you put heart in it, people can generally see it. This is mainly because technical skill is something you'll only get through experience, time and effort, but inspiration is lightning; instantaneous, often forgotten, but sometimes it burns a house down and leaves an imprint in the imagination.
Naturally, the problem there is inspiration comes and goes wildly. You can help coax it out through a couple of means. Reading stories with a similar feel than you're aiming for can certainly do it, or even something as basic as getting a little drunk (don't worry about errors; that's what editing while sober is for), as weakening ones inhibitions sometimes helps me just put absolute weird shit on page that, when I look over it later, isn't as useless as I first thought and just needs a sprucing up.

Experimenting with tenses is also interesting but it's always going to kick you in the teeth to start with. I've always favoured third, but I do have a story in first which was very interesting. I started dabbling in it for specific moments in other stories (like telling someone's journal in the first person, while the surrounding story is third), so maybe bounce around if the story allows, or only use the unfamiliar style for small bursts to get a feel for it, and use your preferred method to relax with.
